In Kubernetes, both cordon and taints are used to control where Pods run, but they solve different problems and operate at different levels.

1. What is cordon?

cordon means:

“Do not schedule NEW pods on this node.”

The node still runs existing pods.

Command:

kubectl cordon <node-name>

Example:

kubectl cordon worker-node-1
What technically happens?

Kubernetes marks the node as:

spec:
  unschedulable: true

Scheduler behavior:

Existing pods → continue running
New pods → NOT scheduled
Manual pods with nodeName → still possible
Real-Time Enterprise Scenario for Cordon

Suppose production node:

worker-node-1

needs:

OS patching
Docker upgrade
Kernel update
Disk replacement
Reboot

DevOps engineer does:

kubectl cordon worker-node-1

Now:

✅ Existing applications continue running
✅ No new workloads enter the node
✅ Safe maintenance preparation

Then usually:

kubectl drain worker-node-1

which evicts existing pods safely.

Important Point

Cordon is:

NODE LEVEL
Temporary operational control
Mainly used by DevOps/SRE teams

NOT an application architecture rule.

2. What is a Taint?

A taint is stronger and more architectural.

It means:

“Pods are NOT allowed here unless they explicitly tolerate this node.”

Command:

kubectl taint nodes worker-node-1 app=database:NoSchedule

Now the node has:

taints:
- key: app
  value: database
  effect: NoSchedule
What happens technically?

Scheduler checks:

Node taints
VS
Pod tolerations

If pod lacks matching toleration:

❌ Scheduler rejects node.

Real-Time Enterprise Use Cases for Taints
Case 1: Dedicated Database Nodes

Company has:

50 worker nodes
5 nodes only for databases

Taint:

kubectl taint nodes db-node-1 dedicated=db:NoSchedule

Only DB pods having:

tolerations:
- key: "dedicated"
  operator: "Equal"
  value: "db"
  effect: "NoSchedule"

can run there.

Case 2: GPU Nodes

GPU machines are costly.

You don’t want normal applications consuming them.

Taint:

kubectl taint nodes gpu-node gpu=true:NoSchedule

Only ML workloads tolerate them.

Case 3: Spot Nodes

In AWS EKS:

cheap spot instances
unstable
can terminate anytime

You taint them:

kubectl taint nodes spot-node lifecycle=spot:NoSchedule

Only fault-tolerant apps tolerate them.

Key Architectural Difference
Feature	Cordon	Taint
Purpose	Stop new scheduling temporarily	Enforce workload placement rules
Level	Operational	Architectural
Existing pods affected?	No	Depends on effect
Requires pod config?	No	Yes (toleration)
Mainly used by	DevOps/SRE	Platform architects
Temporary?	Usually yes	Often permanent
Scheduler behavior	Node marked unschedulable	Scheduler checks taints/tolerations
Taint Effects Deep Dive

There are 3 taint effects.

A) NoSchedule

Most common.

Pods without toleration:
❌ Cannot schedule

Existing pods:
✅ Continue running

Example:

kubectl taint nodes node1 env=prod:NoSchedule
B) PreferNoSchedule

Soft rule.

Scheduler tries to avoid node.

But if needed:
✅ May still schedule.

Useful when:

cluster capacity low
preference only
C) NoExecute

Strongest taint.

Effects:

New pods blocked
Existing pods evicted

Example:

kubectl taint nodes node1 app=db:NoExecute

Pods without toleration:
❌ Cannot enter
❌ Existing pods removed

Real-Time Example of NoExecute

Node becomes unhealthy.

Kubernetes automatically adds taint:

node.kubernetes.io/not-ready

with effect:

NoExecute

Pods get evicted automatically.

This is how Kubernetes self-healing works internally.

Cordon vs Taint Internally
Cordon Flow
kubectl cordon
        ↓
API Server
        ↓
Node.spec.unschedulable=true
        ↓
Scheduler skips node

Simple flag check.

Taint Flow
Pod creation
      ↓
Scheduler
      ↓
Checks node taints
      ↓
Checks pod tolerations
      ↓
Matching?
   YES → Schedule
   NO  → Reject node

More intelligent scheduling logic.

Important Relation Between Them

People often combine:

kubectl cordon
kubectl drain

for maintenance.

Whereas taints are continuously active cluster design rules.

Real Enterprise Comparison
Scenario	Best Choice
Node maintenance	Cordon
OS patching	Cordon
Dedicated infra nodes	Taint
GPU isolation	Taint
Spot instance segregation	Taint
Production-only nodes	Taint
Temporary scheduling stop	Cordon
Prevent noisy neighbors	Taint
One Important Confusion

Many engineers think:

“Cordon is same as taint NoSchedule”

Not exactly.

Because cordon:

ignores tolerations
directly marks node unschedulable

Even admin workloads usually cannot schedule.

Whereas taints:

allow exceptions via tolerations

So taints are more flexible.

Visual Analogy
Cordon
HOTEL CLOSED FOR NEW GUESTS
Existing guests stay.
Taint
VIP ENTRY ONLY
Only guests with permission allowed.
Advanced Real-Time Kubernetes Architecture

Large companies use taints for:

infra nodes
monitoring nodes
logging nodes
GPU pools
ML workloads
batch workloads
stateful workloads
high-memory nodes
ARM nodes
spot instances

Example:

Node Pool A → Web apps
Node Pool B → Databases
Node Pool C → GPU AI
Node Pool D → Monitoring

Each separated using taints/tolerations.

This is core platform engineering in Kubernetes.

Commands Summary
Cordon
kubectl cordon node1
kubectl uncordon node1
Taint

Add taint:

kubectl taint nodes node1 key=value:NoSchedule

Remove taint:

kubectl taint nodes node1 key=value:NoSchedule-
Final Simple Difference
Cordon

“Nobody new enters this node.”

Operational maintenance tool.

Taint

“Only approved pods may enter this node.”

Workload isolation and scheduling policy tool.

