CNI plugin will make sure to bring up ENI with additonal ip's for the upcoming pods to make it ready buffer ip's 

-------------------------------------

This is one of the MOST important deep concepts in Kubernetes + AWS networking.

Once you understand this fully, many confusing things become clear:

Pod IPs
ENIs
VPC CNI
Node networking
Subnets
IP exhaustion
EKS scaling limits
Why pods fail with Insufficient IPs
Why nodes get multiple private IPs

Let’s go layer by layer from AWS infrastructure → Kubernetes networking.

BIG PICTURE FIRST

In AWS EKS:

VPC
 ├── Subnet
 │     ├── EC2 Node
 │     │      ├── ENI
 │     │      │     ├── Primary Private IP
 │     │      │     ├── Secondary Private IPs
 │     │      │
 │     │      ├── Pods
 │     │      │     ├── Pod IP
 │     │      │     ├── Pod IP
 │     │      │     ├── Pod IP

The MOST IMPORTANT thing:

In AWS EKS, Pod IPs come from the VPC subnet itself.

NOT from Docker bridge network like normal Kubernetes.

This is AWS VPC CNI magic.

Step 1 — VPC and Subnets

Suppose you created:

VPC: 10.0.0.0/16

Inside VPC:

Public Subnet: 10.0.1.0/24
Private Subnet: 10.0.2.0/24

Each subnet has:

256 IPs total

AWS reserves 5.

Usable:

251 IPs

These IPs are consumed by:

EC2 nodes
Load balancers
ENIs
Pods (in EKS)
Step 2 — EC2 Node Internal IP

Suppose worker node launches:

EC2 Node
Subnet: 10.0.2.0/24

AWS assigns:

Primary Private IP:
10.0.2.15

This becomes:

Node Internal IP

In Kubernetes:

kubectl get nodes -o wide

shows:

INTERNAL-IP
10.0.2.15
What is Node Internal IP?

It is:

EC2 primary private IP
Used for:
node-to-node communication
kubelet communication
pod routing
cluster internal traffic
Step 3 — Node External IP

If node is public OR attached Elastic IP:

AWS gives:

54.x.x.x

This becomes:

Node External IP

Kubernetes shows:

EXTERNAL-IP
54.x.x.x

Used for:

SSH
internet communication
public access

In production:

worker nodes usually private
no external IP
Step 4 — What is ENI?

ENI means:

Elastic Network Interface

Think of it as:

Virtual Network Card

attached to EC2.

EC2 can have multiple ENIs

Example:

eth0
eth1
eth2

Each ENI:

belongs to one subnet
has:
MAC address
primary private IP
secondary private IPs
VERY IMPORTANT

Pods in EKS use ENI secondary IPs.

This is the core concept.

Example

Suppose node has ENI:

ENI-1
Primary IP:
10.0.2.15

AWS CNI attaches secondary IPs:

10.0.2.20
10.0.2.21
10.0.2.22
10.0.2.23

These secondary IPs are assigned to Pods.

So Pod IPs are REAL VPC IPs

This is VERY important.

In EKS:

Pod IP = actual subnet IP

NOT overlay networking.

This is why:

pods directly communicate
low latency
native AWS routing
Deep Internal Flow
When Pod is Created

Suppose:

kubectl apply -f nginx.yaml

Flow:

Scheduler picks node
       ↓
Kubelet receives pod
       ↓
AWS VPC CNI plugin invoked
       ↓
CNI asks:
"Need IP for pod"
       ↓
ipamd daemon allocates secondary IP
       ↓
Pod network namespace configured
       ↓
Pod gets VPC IP
Who Manages These IPs?

AWS daemon:

aws-node

running in:

kube-system namespace

This contains:

ipamd

(IP Address Management Daemon)

ipamd Responsibilities

It:

allocates ENIs
allocates secondary IPs
keeps warm IP pool
assigns pod IPs
Step 5 — Why Multiple Private IPs on Node?

In AWS Console:

EC2 → Networking

you may see:

Primary IP:
10.0.2.15

Secondary:
10.0.2.20
10.0.2.21
10.0.2.22

These are for Pods.

Why?

Because:

1 Pod = 1 IP

and AWS gives pod IPs through ENIs.

Step 6 — ENI Limits

VERY important in production.

Each EC2 instance type has limits:

Instance	Max ENIs	IPs per ENI
t3.medium	3	6
m5.large	3	10
c5.2xlarge	4	15
Example Calculation

Suppose:

m5.large

supports:

3 ENIs
10 IPs each

Total:

3 × 10 = 30 IPs

But:

primary IP reserved
system overhead

Maximum pods maybe:

~29 pods

This is why EKS has max pod limits.

VERY IMPORTANT RELATION
Pod Scaling depends on IP Scaling

NOT CPU alone.

Many beginners think:

More CPU → more pods

Wrong.

Often:

IP exhaustion occurs first.
Step 7 — Multiple ENIs

When pod count increases:

ENI-1 full

AWS CNI attaches:

ENI-2

with more IPs.

Example:

eth0 → 10 pod IPs
eth1 → 10 pod IPs
eth2 → 10 pod IPs

Pods distributed across ENIs.

Step 8 — Why Subnet Size Matters

Suppose subnet:

10.0.2.0/28

Only:

11 usable IPs

Problem:

nodes consume IPs
pods consume IPs

Cluster quickly fails:

failed to assign IP

Production clusters therefore use:

large CIDRs
dedicated pod subnets
Important Enterprise Issue
IP Exhaustion

Very common in EKS.

Symptoms:

pods stuck pending
CNI errors
node scaling fails

Cause:

subnet ran out of IPs
Step 9 — How Pod Networking Works

Suppose:

Pod-A → 10.0.2.20
Pod-B → 10.0.3.25

Traffic routing:

VPC Route Table
        ↓
AWS native networking
        ↓
Direct routing

No overlay tunneling.

This is why EKS networking is fast.

